{{Infobox person | name = Arthur William Brown | image = | caption = | birth_date = 1881 | death_date = 1966 | occupation = Illustrator | website = | yearsactive = }}
'''Arthur William Brown''' (1881–1966) was a Canadian commercial artist, most known for his work as an illustrator for the ''[[Saturday Evening Post]]'', ''[[American Magazine]]'', and ''[[Redbook]]''.<ref name="HPL">{{cite web|url=http://www.hpl.ca/articles/arthur-william-brown-1881-1966 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-09-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911014136/http://www.hpl.ca/articles/arthur-william-brown-1881-1966 |archivedate=2014-09-11 |df= }}</ref>
==Education and works== [[File:For your boy LCCN00652160.jpg|thumbnail|A YMCA poster created for the United War Work Campaign]] In the 1890s, he attended the [[Hamilton Art School]] and studied under John Gordon. At the age of 16, he was hired as a chalk plate artist for the ''Hamilton Spectator''. He later left Hamilton and attended the Art Students League in [[New York City]], and studied under Walter Appleton Clark, F.W. DuMond, and F.R. Gruger. He was later hired as an illustrator by the ''Saturday Evening Post'', where his works were featured prominently.<ref name="AAA">{{cite web|url=http://www.americanartarchives.com/brown,aw.htm|title=Arthur William Brown|publisher=|accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref>
Brown's works included illustrated stories of American authors such as [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]], [[Irvin Cobb]], such as [[Sinclair Lewis]]. He also illustrated posters for the World War I war effort as well as book cover illustrations.<ref name="HPL"/><ref name="AAA"/>
In 1964, Brown earned the unofficial title of Dean of American Illustrators and was inducted into the Illustrator's Hall of Fame by the American Society of Illustrators.<ref name="HPL"/>
