'''Asada no Yasu''' (麻田陽春) was a poet in Japan's [[Nara period]] who composed both ''[[waka (poetry)|waka]]'' (poetry in Japanese) and ''[[kanshi (poetry)|kanshi]]'' (poetry in Chinese).

== Biography ==
Asada no Yasu was active in the [[Nara period]] of Japanese history.{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}} His birth and death dates are unknown.{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}}

He was a member of the immigrant Tōhon clan (答本氏),{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}} and was originally named Tōhon no Yasu,{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}} but in the [[Japanese calendar|fifth month]] of [[Jinki (era)|Jinki 1]] (724) was given the surname Asada and the hereditary title [[Muraji]], and so became Asada no Muraji Yasu (麻田連陽春).{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}} At this time, he held the court rank of [[List of Japanese court ranks, positions and hereditary titles#Eighth Rank|Senior Eighth Rank, Upper Grade]].{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}}

It is known that by 730 he was working in [[Dazaifu, Fukuoka|Dazaifu]] under [[Ōtomo no Tabito]],{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}} and had attained the [[List of Japanese court ranks, positions and hereditary titles#Sixth Rank|Junior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade]].{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}}

In the first month of 739 he was promoted to the Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade.{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}} According to the ''[[Kaifūsō]]'', during the time he held this rank he became the governor of [[Iwami Province]],{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}} and this was in his [[East Asian age reckoning#Japanese|fifty-sixth year]], but it is unclear when that was.{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}}

He probably lived until around 749.{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}}

== Poetry ==
=== ''Waka'' ===
Four of his ''[[tanka]]'' (the name used for ''[[waka (poetry)|waka]]'' in the standard 5-7-5-7-7 metre in the pre-[[Heian period]]) were included in the ''[[Man'yōshū]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}} These poems were number 569 and 570 (book 4), and 884 and 885 (book 5).{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}} All of these poems were composed during his time at Dazaifu.{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}} Poems 884 and 885 are accompanied by responses from the poet [[Yamanoue no Okura]], so it is clear he had some amount of literary engagement with that poet.{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}}

His socializing with both Tabito and Okura while they were in [[Tsukushi Province|Tsukushi]] has led to speculation that he may have been involved in the compilation of an early form of what became book 5 of the ''Man'yōshū''.{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1pp=41–42}}

=== ''Kanshi'' ===
One ofhis ''[[kanshi (poetry)|kanshi]]'' was included in the ''Kaifūsō''.{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=41}}

He wrote a response to a ''kanshi'' composed by [[Fujiwara no Nakamaro]] during the time the latter was governor of [[Ōmi Province]] (a position he was granted in the ninth month of 747), and this appears to have been composed toward the end of his life.{{sfnm|1a1=Kojima|1y=1983|1p=42}}

