{{Infobox video game |title=Baby Pals |image= Baby Pals.jpg |caption = European cover art of ''Baby Pals'' |developer=Brain Toys |publisher={{vgrelease|JP|[[Interchannel]]|NA|[[Crave Entertainment]]|EU|THQ}} |released ={{vgrelease|NA|November 19, 2007|EU|March 7, 2008|AUS|March 13, 2008|JP|July 17, 2008}} |genre = [[Action game|Action]], [[Life simulation game|life simulation]] |modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]] |platforms = [[Nintendo DS]] }}
'''''Baby Pals''''' is a [[simulation game|simulation-style]] [[video game]] for the [[Nintendo DS]] developed by American studio Brain Toys that released in North America and in the [[PAL]] region in late 2007 and early 2008. The objective of the game is to take care of a virtual baby through certain tasks as feeding, bathing, and teaching just like a real father or mother would do. Players can choose the gender of the baby.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.com/articles/006694/baby-pals/|title=Baby Pals|last=Brice|first=Kath|date=May 2, 2008|website=Pocket Gamer|accessdate=November 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/01/11/baby-pals-review|title=Baby Pals Review|last=Thomas|first=Lucas|date=January 10, 2008|website=IGN|accessdate=November 30, 2018}}</ref>
==Alleged subliminal message== According to news reports, a mother who purchased the game for her child reported that the babies in the game say something that sounds like "[[Islam]] is the light" under certain circumstances. The babies in the game generally do not have any spoken dialog.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wpri.com/dpp/news/strange_news/offbeat_wthi_terrehaute_islam_is_the_light_nintendo_0126200921532177991|title=Video game plays strange message?|last=Hayes|first=Jessica|date=2009-01-27|publisher=WPRI|accessdate=2009-02-02| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090225064058/http://www.wpri.com/dpp/news/strange_news/offbeat_wthi_terrehaute_islam_is_the_light_nintendo_0126200921532177991| archivedate=February 25, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> However, according to a representative from the game's publisher, [[Crave Entertainment]], the sound bit came from "a recording of a 5-month-old baby babbling non-intelligible phrases." He pointed out that "the baby being recorded was too young to pronounce these words let alone a whole grammatically correct phrase."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2009/01/30/crave-responds-to-baby-pals-controversy|title=Crave responds to Baby Pals controversy|last=Fletcher|first=JC|date=2009-01-30|publisher=joystiq|accessdate=2009-02-02| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090202061106/http://www.joystiq.com/2009/01/30/crave-responds-to-baby-pals-controversy| archivedate= 2 February 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
