{{Short description|French sideshow performer known for being extremely thin}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Claude-Ambroise Seurat | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = Claude Ambroise Seurat, a very thin man. Colour etching. Wellcome V0007228.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = Variously listed as:{{unbulleted list|{{Birth date|1797|4|10|df=yes}}<ref name=":0" />|{{Birth date|1798|4|4|df=yes}}<ref name="Redgrave1868" />}} | birth_place = [[Troyes]], France | death_date = after 1833<ref name="Redgrave1868" /> <!--{{Death date and age|????|?|?|1797|4|10}}; prior unsourced death date was 6 April 1826--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | residence = | nationality = French | other_names = {{unbulleted list|Anatomical Man|The Living Human Skeleton}} | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = [[Freak show]] attraction | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = being extraordinarily underweight | home_town = | salary = | height = Variously given as:{{unbulleted list|{{height|ft=5|in=3}} in 1832<ref name="Redgrave1868" />|{{height|ft=5|in=7}} in 1825<ref name=":0" />|{{height|ft=5|in=7+1/2}}<ref name=":1" />}} | weight = {{unbulleted list|{{convert|78|lb|sigfig=3}} in 1825<ref name=":0" />|43 [[Pound (mass)#French livre|French pounds]] in 1832<ref name="Redgrave1868" />}} | movement = | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | footnotes = | box_width = }}
'''Claude-Ambroise Seurat''' (10 April 1797<ref name=":0" /> or 4 April 1798<ref name="Redgrave1868">{{Cite book|last=Redgrave|first=Gilbert R.|author-link=Gilbert Richard Redgrave|date=4 July 1868|chapter=Reply: The Living Skeleton, Claude Ambroise Seurat|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fmoJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA21|title=Notes and Queries: A Medium of Inter-Communication for Literary Men, General Readers, ETC.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fmoJAAAAQAAJ|dead-url=no|series=4th|volume=2|edition=1st|publisher=[[Royal Society of Edinburgh|The Philosophical Institution]]|publication-place=London|publication-date=July–December 1868|page=21|access-date=12 October 2018|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>&nbsp;– after 1833<ref name="Redgrave1868" />) was a [[freak show]] attraction from [[Troyes]], France. He was known as "the anatomical man or the living skeleton" ({{lang-fr|l'homme anatomique ou le squelette vivant}}) due to his extraordinarily low body weight.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://honearchive.org/etexts/edb/day-pages/207-july26.html#img07seurat1| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117080642/http://honearchive.org/etexts/edb/day-pages/207-july26.html#img07seurat1| archive-date=2018-01-17| title=The Every-Day Book| author=William Hone| dead-url=no|access-date=2018-10-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Cissé |first=Joseph de |date=n.d. |title=Description intéressante de Claude-Ambroise Seurat appelé l'homme anatomique, ou le squelette vivant |trans-title=Interesting description of Claude-Ambroise Seurat called the anatomical man, or the living skeleton |url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k5752389g.pleinepage.f1 |location=Nantes |publisher=Victor Mangin}}</ref><ref>Le livre des records, 1984</ref>
== Life == The date of Seurat's birth is uncertain, being variously reported as either 10 April 1797<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Park|first=Richard|last2=Park|first2=Maureen|date=1991-12-21|title=Goya's living skeleton.|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/303/6817/1594|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=303|issue=6817|pages=1594–1596|doi=10.1136/bmj.303.6817.1594|issn=0959-8138|pmid=1820772|via=}}</ref> or 4 April 1798.<ref name="Redgrave1868" /> Seurat's tours across Europe aroused controversy and because of the publicity, there was extensive interest in his life,<ref name=":0" /> particularly from the medical establishment.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Armstrong|first=Rachel|date=1993|title=The role of caricature in medicine|url=|journal=Journal of Audiovisual Media in Medicine|volume=16|pages=165-169|via=}}</ref> An account, for instance, cited that Seurat was born healthy and was normal like other children except for his depressed chest.<ref name=":0" /> By age 14, his health dwindled so that his frame already became skeletal in form.<ref name=":0" /> When he visited [[London]] for a tour in 1825,<ref name=":0" /> Seurat was described having normal height, being between {{convert|5|ft|7|in}}<ref name=":0" /> and {{cvt|5|ft|7+1/2|in|sigfig=3}},<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=The Shows of London|last=Altick|first=Richard Daniel|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1978|isbn=0674807316|location=Cambridge, MA|pages=261}}</ref> but with an emaciated body; at the time, he weighed {{convert|78|lb|sigfig=3}}.<ref name=":0" /> The circumference of his upper arms was {{convert|4|in}}, his waist was less than {{convert|2|ft}} around, while his neck was short, flat, and broad.<ref name=":1" /> Later, in 1832, he was stated to have weighed 43 [[Pound (mass)#French livre|French pounds]] and was {{cvt|5|ft|3|in|m}} tall.<ref name="Redgrave1868" /> Seurat's last recorded performance was in 1833 at [[Dinan]] in [[Brittany]].<ref name="Redgrave1868" />
Seurat was also the subject of an anatomical drawing of [[Francisco Goya]] after the Spanish painter met him in 1826 at a circus in [[Bordeaux]].
The date of Seurat's death is unknown. In 1868, [[Gilbert Richard Redgrave]] commented: "I have not yet been able to ascertain the date of his death. Who knows whether the poor fellow may not still be going the round of the French fairs?"<ref name="Redgrave1868" />
