{{Infobox Judge |honorific-prefix = |name = Michael Ashikodi Agbamuche |honorific-suffix = |image = Agbamuche.jpg |imagesize = |caption = |office = Attorney General & Minister for Justice of Nigeria |term_start = September, 1994 |term_end = 1997 |monarch = |predecessor = Olu Onagoruwa |successor = [[Abdullahi Ibrahim]] |office2 = |term_start2 = |term_end2 = |birth_date = August 16, 1920 |birth_place = [[Oshimili North|Akwukwu-Igbo]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1998|04|17|1920|08|16}} |death_place = |restingplace = |birthname = |nationality = |spouse = |residence = |alma_mater = [[King's College London]] |occupation = |profession = |religion = |signature = |website = |footnotes = }}
'''Michael Ashikodi Agbamuche''' (August 16, 1920 – April 17, 1998) was a former [[Nigerian Federal Ministry of Justice|Attorney General and Minister of Justice]] for [[Nigeria|the Federal Republic of Nigeria]] from September 1994 to 1997, a Senior Advocate of Nigeria ([[Senior Advocate of Nigeria|SAN]]),<ref name="gurusan">{{cite web|title=SENIOR ADVOCATES OF NIGERIA (SAN)|url=http://www.nigerianlawguru.com/information/SENIOR%20ADVOCATES%20OF%20NIGERIA.pdf|website=nigerianlawguru.com|accessdate=March 14, 2016}}</ref> was elected in 1979 to the [[National Assembly of Nigeria|Federal House of Representatives]]<ref name="nwikimh">{{cite web|title=Members of the Nigerian House of Representatives|url=http://nigerianwiki.com/wiki/Members_of_the_Nigerian_House_of_Representatives:Second_republic#Bendel|website=nigerianwiki.com|accessdate=March 14, 2016}}</ref> and the Nnaobodo of [[Oshimili North|Akwukwu-Igbo]].
==Early life and education== Michael Agbamuche was born on August 16, 1920 in [[Oshimili North|Akwukwu-Igbo]] where he attended St John's Anglican primary school. He worked as a clerical officer at the then government secretariat Kaduna until he passed his [[Senior Cambridge]] exams and proceeded to london for further studies. He enrolled in a one-year introduction course at the [[University of Surrey|Battersea Polytechnic Institute]] now the University of Surrey from 1950-1951<ref name="surreyla">{{cite web|title=Battersea lost alumni Year: 1951|url=https://alumni.surrey.ac.uk/sslpage.aspx?pid=997&frcrld=1|website=alumni.surrey.ac.uk|accessdate=March 14, 2016}}</ref>{{failed verification|date = March 2016|reason=source does not specify a course}} before proceeding to [[King's College London School of Law|King's College London]] where he obtained a degree in Law. He was called to the English bar [[Middle Temple]] in 1957. He returned to Nigeria<ref>{{cite web|title=About Nigeria |url=http://www.naijatori.com/about-nigeria/ |website=www.naijatori.com |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817004723/http://www.naijatori.com/about-nigeria/ |archivedate=August 17, 2012 }}</ref> and enrolled as a barrister and solicitor with the [[Supreme Court of Nigeria]] in 1958.
==Career, appointments and politics (timeline)== In 1962, Michael Agbamuche was appointed coroner for Kano and Katsina provinces by Her Majesty, Queen Elizabeth, the Queen of England on the recommendation of the Premier of the Northern region & Sardauna of Sokoto [[Ahmadu Bello|Sir Ahmadu Bello]]. He remained in private legal practice in the northern city of [[Kano State|Kano]] until 1966. In 1967, he was the Principal state counsel, ministry of justice in the Midwestern region. He returned to private practice in Lagos in 1970. In 1976 he went into politics and was elected councillor for Oshimili local government. On the platform of the [[Nigerian People's Party]] (NPP) in 1979 he was elected and became a member of the House of Representatives.<ref name = nwikimh />
In 1984 he was made a Senior Advocate of Nigeria (SAN)<ref name=gurusan /> by the Chief Justice of Nigeria on the recommendation of the Legal Practitioners Privileges Committee. In September 1994 he was appointed Attorney General & Minister for Justice for the Federal Republic of Nigeria, a position he held until 1997. He died on April 17, 1998.
