{{Infobox Officeholder | honorific-prefix = The Hon. | name = Paul Comtois | honorific-suffix = | image = | constituency_MP = [[Nicolet—Yamaska]] | parliament = Canadian | predecessor = [[Maurice Boisvert]] | successor = [[Clément Vincent]] | term_start = June 10, 1957 | term_end = October 12, 1961 | office2 = Lieutenant Governor of Quebec | order2 = 21st | predecessor2 = [[Onésime Gagnon]] | successor2 = [[Hugues Lapointe]] | term_start2 = October 12, 1961 | term_end2 = February 22, 1966 | monarch2 = [[Elizabeth II]] | governor_general2 = [[Georges Vanier]] | premier2 = [[Jean Lesage]] | birth_date = {{birth date|1895|8|22}} | birth_place = Pierreville, Quebec | death_date = {{death date and age|1966|2|21|1895|8|22}} | death_place = Sillery, Quebec | nationality = | spouse = | cabinet = Minister of Mines and Technical Surveys (1957–1961) | party = [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] | relations = [[Charles-Ignace Gill]], grand-nephew | children = | residence = | alma_mater = | occupation = | profession = | religion = }} '''Paul Comtois''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC}} (August 22, 1895 &ndash; February 21, 1966) was a [[Canadian]] politician.
Born in [[Pierreville, Quebec|Pierreville]], [[Quebec]], the son of Urbain Comtois and Elizabeth McCaffrey, he ran unsuccessfully for the [[House of Commons of Canada]] in the [[Canadian federal election, 1930|1930 federal election]] and in a 1933 [[by-election]]. He was elected in [[Canadian federal election, 1957|1957 election]] for the riding of [[Nicolet—Yamaska]]. A [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]], he was re-elected in the [[Canadian federal election, 1958|1958 election]]. From 1957 to 1961, he was the [[Minister of Mines and Technical Surveys (Canada)|Minister of Mines and Technical Surveys]]. In 1961, he was appointed the [[List of lieutenant governors of Quebec#Lieutenant Governors of Quebec, 1867–present|21st]] [[Lieutenant Governor of Quebec]].
He served until 1966, when he was killed in a fire that destroyed his [[Government House (Quebec)|official residence]]. While trying to save the [[Blessed Sacrament]] from the private chapel, he was overcome by the flames.
